Apple and the DMC
-----------------

From John Gruber at Daring Fireball ( https://daringfireball.net/2024/01/ap=
ples_plans_for_the_dma ) :

Apple yesterday announced a broad, wide-ranging, and complex set of new pol=
icies establishing their intended compliance with the European Union=E2=80=
=99s Digital Markets Act, which comes into effect March 7=E2=80=A6

Apple has also argued, consistently, that they seek to monetize third-party=
 development for the iOS platform, and that being forced to change from the=
ir current system=E2=80=89=E2=80=94=E2=80=89(a) all apps must come from the=
 App Store; (b) developers never pay anything for the distribution of free =
apps; (c) paid apps and in-app-purchases for digital content consumed in-ap=
p must go through Apple=E2=80=99s In-App Payments system that automates App=
le=E2=80=99s 30/15 percent commissions=E2=80=89=E2=80=94=E2=80=89would grea=
tly complicate how they monetize the platform. And now Apple has revealed a=
 greatly complicated set of rules and policies for iPhone apps in the EU=E2=
=80=A6

The puzzle Apple attempted to solve was creating a framework of new policie=
s=E2=80=89=E2=80=94=E2=80=89and over 600 new developer APIs to enable those=
 policies=E2=80=89=E2=80=94=E2=80=89to comply with the DMA, while keeping t=
he path of least resistance and risk for developers the status quo: Apple=
=E2=80=99s own App Store as it is.

Here are the changes as summarized by Gruber; I have read Apple=E2=80=99s e=
ntire documentation (and the DMA, for that matter), and do not think I coul=
d do better writing another summary (in part because I collaborated in port=
ions):

Here=E2=80=99s my summary of the options available to developers in the EU,=
 under Apple=E2=80=99s proposal:

* Stay in App Store under the current (pre-DMA) rules, exclusively. Develop=
ers that take this option:

* Are not permitted to use any of the new business terms available in the E=
U, but new iOS platform >options for the EU, such as alternate browser engi=
nes, are allowed. (Because they are required to be allowed.)
* Because nothing business-related changes under this option, the existing =
worldwide rules apply for paid apps, subscriptions, and in-app purchases (I=
AP), including the 30/15 percent commission to Apple and a requirement that=
 apps exclusively use Apple=E2=80=99s App Store payments system.
* The Core Technology Fee (CTF) is not collected, because the business term=
s haven=E2=80=99t changed. (See below re: the CTF.)

* Opt in to the new EU rules (all sub-options available under this choice r=
equire paying the Core Technology Fee for each app with over 1 million down=
loads in the EU):

* After opting in to the new EU rules, developers can choose to
remain in the App Store, and:

* Use Apple=E2=80=99s App Store payments system: 20/13 percent commission +=
 CTF paid to Apple automatically.
* Use a custom in-app payments system (e.g. Stripe): 17/10 percent commissi=
on + CTF paid to Apple.
* Use external links from inside apps to the web for payments and subscript=
ions: 17/10 percent + CTF paid to Apple.
* The latter two options =E2=80=94 using custom payment processing and/or e=
xternal links to the web =E2=80=94 are similar to the announced-last-week E=
xternal Payment Link entitlement policy ( https://developer.apple.com/suppo=
rt/storekit-external-entitlement-us/ ) , regarding the developer=E2=80=99s =
obligation to track these payments, report sales to Apple monthly, and subm=
it to audits by Apple to ensure compliance.

* Distribute apps in one or more third-party marketplaces:

* No option to use Apple=E2=80=99s App Store payment processing, because th=
e apps aren=E2=80=99t coming from the App Store.
* The only money due to Apple is the Core Technology Fee =E2=80=94 there is=
 no commission percentage on in-app transactions or links to the web.

Under option (2) =E2=80=94 the catch-all for opting in to the new rules ava=
ilable in the EU =E2=80=94 the sub-options are not mutually exclusive. Deve=
lopers that opt in to the new EU rules can have (or keep) apps in the App S=
tore and distribute those same apps, or different apps, via third-party app=
 marketplaces. Or they can stay in the App Store exclusively (under the new=
 business terms, with lower commissions but also the CTF), or they can dist=
ribute exclusively via app marketplaces.

Only options (1) and (2) are exclusive. However, once a developer opts in t=
o the new EU rules, that decision is irrevocable. Quoting from the Q&A sect=
ion of Apple=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CUpdate on Apps Distributed in the European =
Union=E2=80=9D document ( https://developer.apple.com/support/dma-and-apps-=
in-the-eu/#faq ) :

Developers who adopt the new business terms at any time will not
be able to switch back to Apple=E2=80=99s existing business terms for
their EU apps. Apple will continue to give developers advance
notice of changes to our terms, so they can make informed choices
about their businesses moving forward.

The Core Technology Fee ( https://developer.apple.com/support/dma-and-apps-=
in-the-eu/#faq ) is =E2=82=AC0.50 per install of an app per account per yea=
r, in excess of 1 million installs. As Gruber explains:

In plain language, the DMA demands that Apple unbundle its monetization for=
 the App Store from its monetization of the iOS platform. Apple=E2=80=99s e=
xisting, purely commission-based, monetization for iOS apps implicitly bund=
les together the value provided from the App Store and iOS.

So under option (1)=E2=80=89=E2=80=94=E2=80=89where developers choose the e=
xisting rules for App Store distribution, including App Store exclusivity=
=E2=80=89=E2=80=94=E2=80=89nothing changes and Apple collects its 30/15 per=
cent commissions from App Store transactions.

But under option (2)=E2=80=89=E2=80=94=E2=80=89where developers opt in to t=
he new EU rules=E2=80=89=E2=80=94=E2=80=89Apple=E2=80=99s monetization for =
the App Store is severed from its monetization for the iOS platform itself.=
 That=E2=80=99s why the commission fees under the new EU rules are reduced =
to 20/13 percent for apps distributed through the App Store that use the Ap=
p Store payment system, and 17/10 percent for apps distributed through the =
App Store that use custom payment processing. Effectively, Apple is saying =
that their fair share of App Store distribution is 17/10 percent, and that =
Apple=E2=80=99s own App Store payment processing is worth an additional 3 p=
ercent. (3 percent is almost indisputably a fair estimate for the cost of p=
ayment processing alone.)

And, that=E2=80=99s why apps distributed outside the App Store will only pa=
y Apple the CTF, with no commission on sales. The commissions under the new=
 EU rules are only for the App Store, so apps from marketplaces don=E2=80=
=99t pay them. The Core Technology Fee is how Apple proposes monetizing the=
 value provided by iOS itself.

All developers who opt in to the new EU rules are subject to the CTF. No de=
velopers who remain in the App Store under existing policies are subject to=
 the CTF.

There are a few extra additional points to understand about the new regime:

* There is no direct side-loading of apps, like from a developer=E2=80=99s =
website; rather, companies can set up alternative app marketplaces (by regi=
stering with Apple and having a =E2=82=AC1 million line of credit).
* Apps can only be installed from one marketplace at a time; if Spotify, sa=
y, wanted to set up their own marketplace, they could not overwrite existin=
g Spotify installs, but would have to hope users delete the one they have a=
nd install a new one.
* Apple will still review all apps on alternative app marketplaces, but not=
 for content: they will scan for malware and the use of private APIs, enfor=
ce App Tracking Transparency, and other vagaries around security (this step=
 will include human review).

