ly hung up on money, specifically Apple=E2=80=99s 30%, which Apple has now =
informed us is about 2/3 for the App Store and 1/3 for the access to iOS. A=
nd with that, let me return to my caveat: I believe that Apple has been rew=
arded handsomely for iOS, both in terms of profits and in control, and I wi=
sh they would not charge developers for iOS.

At the same time, there simply is no question that iOS is Apple=E2=80=99s i=
ndividual property, and if they wish to charge for it, they can: for it to =
be otherwise would require taking their property and basically nationalizin=
g it (while, I assume, demanding they continue to take care of it). It is f=
rustrating that Apple has insisted on driving us to this fundamental realit=
y, but reality it is, and the DMA isn=E2=80=99t going to change that.

Given that reality =E2=80=94 which again, I wish we didn=E2=80=99t have to =
face, but which we must given Apple=E2=80=99s insistence on monetizing thei=
r property =E2=80=94 it=E2=80=99s important to acknowledge that the current=
 App Store approach is the optimal way for Apple to monetize said intellect=
ual property, not just from their perspective, but from society=E2=80=99s a=
s well. To review, apps are free to publish on the App Store, and 30% of al=
l digital goods must be shared with Apple. That means that there is maximum=
 latitude for new entrants, and any and all payments are taken out of zero =
marginal cost revenue, which minimizes the harm from any sort of =E2=80=9Ct=
ax=E2=80=9D. This is an approach that maximizes innovation and minimizes de=
adweight loss.

Just compare this to the E.U. alternative: the CTF institutes a marginal co=
st per user that scales independent of revenue. Indeed, a free or freemium =
software developer who goes viral could go bankrupt overnight. That=E2=80=
=99s not good for innovation! Sure, you can keep more money when you moneti=
ze, but your likelihood of monetizing successfully is lower given the disin=
centives in place for pursuing growth and virality upfront. Note too that t=
he exact same critique would apply if Apple simply jacked up the developer =
fee from $99 a year: Apple could charge companies millions of dollars to wr=
ite software on iOS, but that would basically eliminate new entrants comple=
tely.

Again, most developers =E2=80=94 and me =E2=80=94 would prefer to have thei=
r cake and eat it too: to have the option to pursue a freemium model on iOS=
 without the fear of bankruptcy from virality and also share less money wit=
h Apple. And there are some developers who, given that Apple competes direc=
tly with them (i.e. Spotify), arguably deserve that opportunity. For my par=
t I think more freedom in business models =E2=80=94 my modest request is th=
at non-games be allowed to link to the web for payments without being audit=
ed by Apple =E2=80=94 would spur more innovation.

At some point, though, everyone has to make a choice, because Apple already=
 has: given it has staked its claim to its intellectual property and the ri=
ght to monetize it, the E.U. will have to decide whether or not Apple is ab=
iding by their impossible-to-abide-by regulation, and developers will have =
to decide if they want Apple=E2=80=99s old business model or the new one. B=
oth parties would probably do well to accept things as they were, particula=
rly given the evidence of any consumer harm =E2=80=94 at least once you dis=
miss theoretical apps that were never created =E2=80=94=C2=A0not only doesn=
=E2=80=99t exist but actually runs in the opposite direction.

